explanation:
To determine whether any operations in OS_CreateSocketName constitute dead code (i.e., they are executed but could be removed without changing program behaviour) the analyzer needs the following symbols and why:

- OS_stream_internal_record_t: The function writes into sock->stream_name. The structure definition is required to know the type, size and semantics of stream_name and whether other fields or invariants mean these writes are redundant.

- OS_stream_table: OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET returns an entry from this table. The table declaration and lifetime semantics are needed to know whether the written stream_name persists, is later overwritten, or is unused (which affects whether writes are necessary).

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: This macro/function maps the token to a table entry (sock). Its implementation (and whether it uses OS_ObjectIndexFromToken) is required to see if the access is guaranteed to yield a valid entry and whether any side-effects make the code necessary.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type semantics (valid/invalid token cases) influence whether OS_CreateSocketName is ever called with a token that makes the body no-op or redundant; also relevant for understanding OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Shown in the call graph as a callee of the macro; its semantics (side-effects, errors) are needed to determine whether the macro invocation contributes required behaviour (e.g., index validation) or is dead relative to other effects.

- OS_SocketAddrToString_Impl: This call populates the initial textual representation of the socket address. Its behaviour (when it returns OS_SUCCESS, whether it writes the buffer, whether its output is ever consumed) is central to determining whether the subsequent buffer writes are necessary.

- OS_SocketAddrGetPort_Impl: This provides the port used in the ":%u" append. Knowing when it returns OS_SUCCESS and whether the returned port is used elsewhere is required to determine if the port-append code can be removed without changing behaviour.

- OS_SUCCESS: The code compares return values against this constant. Its value and semantic meaning must be known to reason about which branches execute and whether they are no-ops.

- OS_strnlen: Used to compute append offsets. Its exact behaviour (especially boundary behaviour with non-terminated buffers) matters to know whether code is defensive/necessary or redundant.

- OS_SocketBindAddress: One of the callers; required to inspect how OS_CreateSocketName is invoked (arguments, parent_name value) and whether the name written by OS_CreateSocketName is subsequently used by the caller. If callers never use the produced stream_name (or always overwrite it later), some writes may be dead.

- OS_SocketAccept: The other direct caller; needed for the same reason as OS_SocketBindAddress (to see parent_name usage and subsequent use of stream_name), and to understand calling contexts in which parts of OS_CreateSocketName may be unnecessary.

Including these symbols lets the next analysis determine (a) which branches actually execute at runtime, (b) whether the writes to sock->stream_name affect observable behaviour (used by callers or later code), and (c) whether any executed statements could be removed without changing program behaviour, per the MISRA dead-code rule.
